/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ugilfalas.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gilfalas</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Administrator</span><br>  Posts: 1496<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/27/02 1:15:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathfrm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=1>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Bane and Magic Damage Effects</span><hr size=1> Bane weapons add the bane damage listed to the weapon base damage against the specified Creature type listed. So a 14/24 one hander with bane 10 versus dragons would be 24/24 veruss dragons.<br><br>Elemental and magic damage ratings work similaly, but the mob gets a resist check versus the bonus damage, unlike bane weapons who always add the damage rating versus the specified mobs.<br><br>So a 14/24 one hander with 10 Fire damage would hit a mob, do a resist check and if the mob failed would be 14/24 with an added simultaneous 10 damage attack in the same swing using the same attack value as the swing itself to determine damage. <br><br>Off hand elemental and magic weapons have been reported to hit for 2 minimum leading to this theory of combat resolution. Bane weapons on the other hand have not had such reports when used off hand.<br><br>These are still mostly speculation on how EXACTLY they work, but this guide shoudl be pretty accurate. <p><center><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=105286">Gilfalas Elaandrin</a>, Lvl 59 Knight of Tunare & Defender of Nature<br>Bertoxxulous Server<br><a href="http://pub13.ezboard.com/bpaladinsofnorrath">Paladins Of Norrath</a> Messageboard Admin<br>Member of <a href="http://www.fedupnow.com/">Dragon Council</a><br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ubizomb.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bizomb</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 878<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/27/02 1:29:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathfrm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Bane and Magic Damage Effects</span><hr size=1> So you are saying it's almost like using 2 weapons and accumulating the effects?<br>like swinging a 14/24 and 10/24 at the same time and adding the damage together. Which gives the 2 on offhand min.<br>hmmm. And it would be reasonably easy to code that way, just put them both on the same swing timer and add the results at the end.<br>Throw the damage calculated by your elemental 10/24 portion of the weapon through a resist check to see how much you add to the other part of the weapon.<br>Makes sense.<br>I was trying to figure out how they would calculate it, this seems to be a pretty reasonable solution.<br><br>Biz.<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathfrm12.showPrevMessage?topicID=319.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathfrm12.showNextMessage?topicID=319.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathfrm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=2><img src=http://eq1.castersrealm.com/pon/images/reply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathfrm12.emailToFriend?topicID=319.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Fr